You need to create a component. E.g. `ProductComponent` is your view and then in `app.module.ts`(or another module) you should write your routing:

    @NgModule({
      declarations: [
        ProductFormComponent,
        AdminProductComponent,
        AdminOrderComponent
      ],
      imports: [
        SharedModule,
        RouterModule.forRoot([          
          { path: &#39;products/:id&#39;,
            component: ProductComponent
          },
          { path: &#39;admin/products&#39;,
            component: AdminProductComponent
          },
          {
            path: &#39;admin/orders&#39;,
            component: AdminOrderComponent
          }
        ])
      ]      
    })
    export class AppModule { }

Let&#39;s see this path: `path: &#39;products/:id&#39;`, where `products/` is your view(like in Django)
and `:id` is `id` of your item(`product`)

[More info can be seen here in Angular docs][1]


  [1]: https://angular.io/guide/router#route-definition-with-a-parameter

You can set this entry in your router config: 
```
{ path: &#39;view/:id&#39;, component: ViewComponent }
```

And then access the `id` with: 
```
constructor(
  private route: ActivatedRoute,
) { }
   
ngOnInit() {
  this.route.params.subscribe( params =&gt; {
    this.id = params.id;
    console.log(this.id) 
  });
}
```

You can put an component on a route in your `rouing.module`.

    const routes: Routes = [
      {path: &#39;&#39;, component: FirstComponent},
