`this.state.title[1]`, `this.state.title[0]` are `undefined` till you make the `GET` request.

You should add a condition before trying to `map` undefined value or add `state` initial value:

```
const CardContainer = ({ weatherData }) =&gt; (
  &lt;main&gt;{weatherData &amp;&amp; weatherData.map(day =&gt; &lt;p&gt;{day}&lt;/p&gt;)}&lt;/main&gt;
);

// Or adding an initial value
class App extends Component {
  state = {
    title: [&#39;initial1&#39;, &#39;initial2&#39;]
  };
  ....
}
```

Also note that by using [babel&#39;s arrow functions as class properties][1] (enabled by default), you can avoid binding every function to `this` (which is error-prone).

```
// Avoid &lt;SearchBox getRequest={this.getTitle.bind(this)} /&gt;
// Using class arrow function:

class App extends Component {
  getTitle = title =&gt; {
     ....
  };

  // use this.getTitle(...) without binding
}
```


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49350702/arrow-functions-as-class-properties-using-babel

