It is because of the order of evaluation, that is altered using parentheses. The first code is actually:

    var foo = (false &amp;&amp; false) ? true : true;

Which means:

    if (false&amp;&amp;false)
     foo=true;
    else
     foo=true;

The second is:

`var bar = false &amp;&amp; (false ? true : true);`

Which means

    bool x    
    if (false)
     x=true;
    else
     x=true;
    if (false&amp;&amp;x)
     bar=true;
    else
     bar=false;

One pair of parentheses changes everything.

